# Third‑Party Tools Used in Lift‑and‑Shift Cloud Migration

## Introduction

When migrating an application from on‑premises to the cloud using the Lift‑and‑Shift approach, organizations may use either native cloud tools (like AWS MGN, DMS) or third‑party tools. Third‑party tools are commonly used because they support multiple cloud providers, provide advanced disaster recovery features, and simplify migration with automation.

This document summarizes some important third‑party migration tools, what they do, how they connect, and how they are used in real migration scenarios.

---

# 1. CloudEndure (Now part of AWS Application Migration Service)

## What it does

CloudEndure is a migration and disaster recovery tool that replicates entire servers including operating system, applications, configurations, and data from on‑premises infrastructure to the cloud with minimal downtime.

## How it connects

CloudEndure works by installing a lightweight replication agent on the source (on‑premises) server. This agent continuously replicates disk data to a staging environment in the cloud through secure HTTPS communication.

## How it is used

Typical workflow:

1. Install CloudEndure agent on on‑prem server
2. Start continuous data replication
3. CloudEndure creates a replica in cloud
4. Test the migrated server
5. Perform cutover to cloud

## When companies use it

• Lift and shift migrations
• Disaster recovery setups
• Large scale server migrations

---

# 2. Zerto

## What it does

Zerto is a disaster recovery and migration platform that provides continuous data protection and real‑time replication of virtual machines.

## How it connects

Zerto integrates with virtualization platforms like:

• VMware
• Microsoft Hyper‑V

It performs block‑level replication of virtual machines between data centers and cloud environments.

## How it is used

Typical workflow:

1. Install Zerto Virtual Manager
2. Connect virtualization environment
3. Select virtual machines for replication
4. Start continuous replication
5. Trigger failover when required

## When companies use it

• Disaster recovery planning
• VM migration
• Business continuity solutions

---

# 3. Carbonite Migrate

## What it does

Carbonite Migrate is a server migration tool that moves physical and virtual servers to cloud environments with minimal downtime.

## How it connects

Carbonite installs an agent on the source server which continuously transfers system data to the target cloud server.

## How it is used

Typical workflow:

1. Install Carbonite migration agent
2. Start replication process
3. Monitor synchronization
4. Test migrated system
5. Perform final cutover

## When companies use it

• Physical to cloud migration
• Data center migration
• Legacy system migration

---

# 4. Veeam

## What it does

Veeam is primarily a backup and disaster recovery solution, but it is also used for cloud migration by restoring backups into cloud environments.

## How it connects

Veeam connects using:

• Backup agents
• Virtualization APIs
• Cloud storage connectors

It stores backups in cloud storage and restores them into cloud virtual machines.

## How it is used

Typical workflow:

1. Take full backup of on‑prem server
2. Store backup in cloud storage
3. Restore backup into cloud VM
4. Start application in cloud

## When companies use it

• Backup and recovery
• Hybrid cloud backup
• Migration through backup restore

---

# 5. Rsync

## What it does

Rsync is an open‑source file synchronization tool used to transfer and synchronize files between servers efficiently.

## How it connects

Rsync connects using SSH between the on‑premises server and the cloud server.

## How it is used

Typical workflow:

1. Establish SSH connection
2. Run rsync command
3. Transfer files incrementally
4. Synchronize only changed files

## Example command

rsync -avz /localdata user@cloudserver:/data

## When companies use it

• File migration
• Backup synchronization
• DevOps automation scripts

---

# Tool Comparison Summary

| Tool        | Main Purpose                         |
| ----------- | ------------------------------------ |
| CloudEndure | Full server migration                |
| Zerto       | Disaster recovery and VM replication |
| Carbonite   | Server migration                     |
| Veeam       | Backup and recovery migration        |
| Rsync       | File synchronization                 |

---

# Simple Interview Summary

Third‑party tools like CloudEndure, Zerto, Carbonite, Veeam, and Rsync help migrate servers, replicate data, perform backups, and synchronize files when moving applications from on‑premises to cloud environments.

---

# Key Takeaway

In Lift‑and‑Shift migration, third‑party tools help organizations:

• Reduce downtime
• Automate migration
• Maintain data consistency
• Improve disaster recovery
• Simplify hybrid cloud operations

---

# One Line Conclusion

Third‑party migration tools help move servers, data, and applications from on‑premises to cloud efficiently while minimizing downtime and operational risks.

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


Active-Passive Multi-Cloud Architecture (5 simple lines):

1.In this architecture, the application runs actively in one cloud (primary like AWS) while another cloud (secondary like Azure) stays as standby.

2.Data is continuously replicated from the active cloud to the passive cloud to keep both synchronized.

3.Monitoring tools check the health of the primary cloud continuously.

4.If the primary cloud fails, traffic automatically shifts to the secondary cloud (failover).

5.This improves reliability, disaster recovery, and ensures high availability with minimal downtime.
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Infrastructure Migration

Instead of manually creating everything, companies use Infrastructure as Code (IaC).

Infrastructure as Code (IaC) means you write a small configuration file that describes what infrastructure you want, and the tool creates it automatically instead of manually clicking in the cloud portal.
Example:
Instead of manually creating:
1 VM
1 Network
1 Load balancer
You write a Terraform file saying:
"Create 1 Azure VM with 4GB RAM inside a VNet with a load balancer" → Terraform creates everything automatically.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Connect to cloud providers – Terraform connects to AWS or Azure using provider plugins and API credentials.
This means Terraform uses provider plugins (AWS provider, Azure provider) and your cloud access keys (API credentials) to log in and communicate with the cloud.

Example:
You give Terraform your AWS access key or Azure subscription details → Terraform uses cloud APIs to create VMs, networks, and storage automatically.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Plan the infrastructure – Terraform checks what resources are needed and shows an execution plan (what will be created/changed).

This means Terraform first compares your code with the current cloud setup and tells you what it is going to do before actually doing it.
Example:
If your code says create 1 VM and 1 VNet, Terraform shows a plan like:
+ create Azure VM
+ create Azure VNet
so you can review it before applying.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Apply the configuration – When you run terraform apply, it automatically creates VMs, networks, and other resources in the target cloud.

This means when you run terraform apply, Terraform sends requests through cloud APIs and automatically creates the infrastructure you defined in the configuration file.
Example:
If your code says:
Create 1 Azure VM
Create 1 VNet
Create 1 Load balancer
After terraform apply → Terraform automatically creates all these resources without manual setup.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Maintain consistency – If infrastructure changes later, Terraform updates only the required parts to keep the setup consistent.
This means Terraform compares the current infrastructure with your updated code and changes only what is different, instead of recreating everything.
Example:
If you change VM RAM from 4 GB → 8 GB in the Terraform file, Terraform will only update the VM size and leave the network and load balancer unchanged.

Simple idea:
Terraform keeps infrastructure matching your code (source of truth) by updating only the necessary parts.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


Roll Back Strategy
A rollback strategy is a backup plan to return to the previous working system if migration or deployment fails.
It is used to avoid downtime and data loss if the new system has errors.
It usually involves keeping the old system running until the new one is fully tested.
It is used during cloud migration, deployments, and updates (Blue-Green or Canary deployments).


ow i am moving my application to my new cloud because i have some disasters or failures in old cloud. Due to some issues i am moving from old to new cloud . And now my new cloud also have some errors

In this situation, companies follow a multi-level disaster recovery strategy so they are never dependent on just one cloud.
What is done (simple concept):
Rollback to old cloud (if still usable) – If possible, traffic is moved back temporarily.
Use third backup location – Either another cloud or backup region.
Restore from backups – Database backups and storage snapshots are used.
Fix issues in new cloud while service runs elsewhere – This is called failover + failback strategy.

Real industry practice:
Companies usually follow 3-2-1 rule:

3 copies of data
2 different environments
1 offsite backup
Simple idea:
Never depend on just one backup cloud — always keep multiple recovery options to avoid total failure.
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


Terraform ---> A script is written so that it creates the VMs, Load balancer according to the specifications given in the script. Along with it the credentials have to be given.

